ose and plays, becoming a respected and prolific author of her time and part of W.B. Yeats’ literary circle. The story of Gore-Booth’s life is captivating. Her close bond with her sister, an iconic Irish nationalist, provides a new insight into Countess Markievicz’s personal life. Gore-Booth’s life story vividly traces her experiences of issues such as militant pacifism during the Great War, the case for the reprieve of Roger Casement’s death sentence, sexual equality in the workplace and the struggle for Irish independence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen social reformerszIrelandvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aEva Gore- Booth.  aGreat War.  aIrish independence.  aIrish woman.  aRoger Casement.  aW.B. Yeats.  aWinston Churchill.  aaristocratic heritage.  agender equality.  aindustrial Manchester.  amilitant pacifism.  aoccult beliefs.  asexual equality.  aspiritualism.1 aTiernan, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978071909499640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780719094996423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780719094996/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles